CMOS technology scaling has created a set of new challenges and opportunities for the realization of analog &amp; mixed-signal (AMS) and radio frequency (RF) circuits. The size and complexity of AMS/RF circuits are growing as the designer strives to deliver higher performance and more functionality.  At the same time, analog components have been increasingly integrated with digital processors under the context of mixed-signal systems-on-a-chips. Nevertheless, developing analog functionalities in highly scaled CMOS technologies is hampered by worsening analog device characteristics such as deteriorating output impedance, reduced supply level and headroom, growing device mismatch, and higher susceptibility to noise and process variation. In the meantime, the notion of digitally-intensive or digitally-assisted analog design methodology has emerged, which leverages the abundance of digital processing offered by modern CMOS technologies to assist the development of AMS and RF systems.

As a result, there has been an increasing need in developing efficient methodologies for verifying, testing and tuning of AMS systems including digitally-intensive analog circuits. To achieve this goal, throughout this project, the two collaborating teams at Texas A&amp;M University and University of Utah have made a number of contributions including:



A user friendly property language for describing attributes that a correct AMS circuit must have;
A means to create accurate, formal models from simulation data;
SMT-based formal techniques for verifying static properties of AMS circuits;
Efficient and sound reachability analysis for formal verification of dynamic properties of AMS circuits;
Methods for diagnosis of out-of-specification failures of AMS circuits using pre-silicon data;
A machine-learning based performance modeling, verification, and built-in-self-test (BIST) of AMS circuits; and
A methodology for functional testing of AMS circuits.




Along the above lines, a coherent set of technical contributions have been made as summarized in a book chapter, two journal papers, ten conference papers, and five workshop presentations published under this project.

Broadly, this project addresses the urgent need for developing methodologies and tools for developing highly robust analog/mixed-signal and RF integrated circuits which are key to a broad range of applications in communication, signal processing, and computing.  The results of this work may be broadly applicable to several other science and engineering disciplines such as cyber-physical systems. The two PIs have integrated the outcomes of this project into the graduate-level curricula at Texas A&amp;M University and University of Utah. The results of this project have been disseminated widely to academia, industry, and the general public through publications, and invited talks at conferences and industrial sites. Industrial research collaboration has been actively pursued to provide the students with real-world exposure and promote the industrial adoption of this work throughout this project. A number of Ph. D. and M. S. graduate student researchers have been trained. Among these, three Ph. D. students and two M.S. student have graduated and joined the US high-tech industry.





